  "text": "Disturbances in the sleep-wake rhythm and deprivation are increasingly frequent due to even are progressively more common in modern life i developed countries [CITATION_1] . Man jects can be chronically sleep-deprived as a re their current lifestyle [CITATION_2] . Sleep d tion can lead to traffic accidents due to fatigue an ations in the biological rhythm. Indeed, 16% of ian interstate bus drivers reported sleepiness whil ing, with an average of eight naps/trip (De Mell 2000) , and 38% of those drivers have been dia with obstructive sleep apnea (Santos et al. 2004 cently, a new legislation was approved that will new medical and psychological examinations Brazilian drivers. These examinations will be i \"main \" -2009/7/27 -14:50 - [CITATION_3] ). An epidemiological study performed by the Department of Psychobiology of Unifesp in the city of São Paulo has shown that, in 1995, 27.6% (1.7 million) of inhabitants of São Paulo complained of difficulty in staying asleep. Furthermore, habitual snoring was the most common complaint and was reported by about 20% of the interviewees [CITATION_4] ). In 2007, obstructive sleep apnea syndrome was found in 32.8% of the population of São Paulo, Brazil (S. Tufik et al., unpublished data) . Sleep has a cyclical or episodic phase that alternates with wakefulness. An important characteristic of sleep that differentiates it from most of other states of altered consciousness is that it is promptly reversible.",
